259
00:08:40,192 --> 00:08:42,121
I preferred melodicas to xylophones.

260
00:08:42,122 --> 00:08:43,462
- Melodicas. Yes.
- Right?

261
00:08:44,462 --> 00:08:45,731
(The members are engrossed in reminiscing about the past.)

262
00:08:45,732 --> 00:08:46,861
- This is crazy.
- I want to go back in time...

263
00:08:46,862 --> 00:08:47,961
just for ten seconds.

264
00:08:47,962 --> 00:08:49,601
No, not 10 seconds. Maybe, 1 day or 1 week.

265
00:08:49,602 --> 00:08:51,631
I'd love to time travel to the 90s just for a week.

266
00:08:51,632 --> 00:08:53,372
- I want to go back as myself.
- Right.

267
00:08:53,642 --> 00:08:54,802
I wonder how that would feel.

268
00:08:55,702 --> 00:08:58,472
Seriously. I'd love to go back in time just for 1 or 2 days.

269
00:08:58,572 --> 00:09:00,442
Same here. I'd love to go back in time.

270
00:09:00,642 --> 00:09:01,781
- Really?
- Yes.

271
00:09:01,782 --> 00:09:04,381
I can think about the old days and have fun.

272
00:09:04,382 --> 00:09:06,011
- You're young at heart.
- Right.

273
00:09:06,012 --> 00:09:08,281
All right. Let's start the first mission...

274
00:09:08,282 --> 00:09:10,051
of the Time Capsule Race.

275
00:09:10,052 --> 00:09:11,822
The game you will play here is called...

276
00:09:12,252 --> 00:09:14,061
Initial Game with Real Items.

277
00:09:14,062 --> 00:09:15,938
- Initial Game with Real Items?
- Initial Game with Real Items.

278
00:09:15,962 --> 00:09:17,191
I guess we have to grab them.

279
00:09:17,192 --> 00:09:18,661
- I don't know this game.
- Okay.

280
00:09:18,662 --> 00:09:20,231
Just like the name of the game,

281
00:09:20,232 --> 00:09:22,631
you must bring back the item corresponding to the initials.

282
00:09:22,632 --> 00:09:23,952
- Okay.
- There are tons of them.

283
00:09:24,172 --> 00:09:25,431
- There are...
- You're distracting me.

284
00:09:25,432 --> 00:09:26,501
Stop moving around.

285
00:09:26,502 --> 00:09:28,001
- He keeps...
- He prepared a lot for today.

286
00:09:28,002 --> 00:09:30,742
He's making me sick. I'm about to get motion sickness.

287
00:09:31,772 --> 00:09:33,581
Your body rolls are giving motion sickness.

288
00:09:33,582 --> 00:09:34,642
I'm a big shot, you know.

289
00:09:34,842 --> 00:09:38,212
The team that takes 2 out of 3 rounds wins.

290
00:09:38,582 --> 00:09:41,351
The winning team will receive ten time capsules.

291
00:09:41,352 --> 00:09:43,052
- I see.
- Let's set it up now.

292
00:09:43,392 --> 00:09:44,392
Great.

293
00:09:44,892 --> 00:09:45,992
- In the back.
- Great.

294
00:09:46,722 --> 00:09:47,722
What's that?

295
00:09:47,723 --> 00:09:48,792
(A board is covered up.)

296
00:09:50,332 --> 00:09:51,692
"A, B, C, D, E, F..."

297
00:09:52,532 --> 00:09:54,761
For the first round of Initial Game with Real Items,

298
00:09:54,762 --> 00:09:57,178
you must obtain more consonant cards than your opposing team.

299
00:09:57,202 --> 00:09:58,471
- Consonant cards?
- Consonant cards.

300
00:09:58,472 --> 00:09:59,472
- Consonant cards?
- Okay.

301
00:09:59,473 --> 00:10:01,841
One member of each team can bring an object in a relay race.

302
00:10:01,842 --> 00:10:04,742
Your team can obtain the consonants based on the item's initials then.

303
00:10:04,912 --> 00:10:07,482
However, there's only one card for each consonant.

304
00:10:07,612 --> 00:10:10,612
So you can't use the consonants that are already used.

305
00:10:11,112 --> 00:10:13,251
For example, if you bring an iron,

306
00:10:13,252 --> 00:10:15,398
you will obtain the cards for digeut, rieul, and mieum.

307
00:10:15,422 --> 00:10:17,122
Your time limit is five minutes.

308
00:10:17,522 --> 00:10:20,021
The team with more consonant cards will win.

309
00:10:20,022 --> 00:10:21,091
- More consonant cards?
- Yes.

310
00:10:21,092 --> 00:10:23,008
Then isn't it more advantageous to bring an item with long names?

311
00:10:23,032 --> 00:10:24,232
- Right.
- Everyone.

312
00:10:24,432 --> 00:10:25,761
- Then I can go first...
- They can't take the same cards.

313
00:10:25,762 --> 00:10:27,131
- Yes, you're right.
- and get an item with a long name.

314
00:10:27,132 --> 00:10:29,338
- You can also bring them.
- So we can't overlap, right?

315
00:10:29,362 --> 00:10:31,102
- What?
- And...

316
00:10:31,532 --> 00:10:32,771
(Jong Min didn't understand the rules.)

317
00:10:32,772 --> 00:10:34,118
He said we couldn't overlap, right?

318
00:10:34,142 --> 00:10:35,142
We can.

319
00:10:35,143 --> 00:10:36,788
(Joon didn't understand the rules either.)

320
00:10:36,812 --> 00:10:38,571
(Smirking)

321
00:10:38,572 --> 00:10:40,311
Why did you pair Jong Min and Joon up together?

322
00:10:40,312 --> 00:10:42,192
- What do you mean?
- Why did you pair them up?

323
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:44,412
Was it because they're both fools?

324
00:10:44,612 --> 00:10:45,981
- Because we're good.
- Because they're not so bright?

325
00:10:45,982 --> 00:10:47,651
- Because we're successful.
- We wanted the game...

326
00:10:47,652 --> 00:10:50,012
- to have a lot of tension.
- I'm going to do it like this.

327
00:10:50,222 --> 00:10:51,922
- You're ready, right?
- Okay.

328
00:10:52,092 --> 00:10:53,921
If we win the first one, the rest will be easy.

329
00:10:53,922 --> 00:10:54,991
- Okay.
- Got it?

330
00:10:54,992 --> 00:10:55,992
Okay.

331
00:10:56,262 --> 00:10:57,432
Get ready.

332
00:10:58,032 --> 00:10:59,061
- Which way will you go?
- Go!

333
00:10:59,062 --> 00:11:00,102
Over there.

334
00:11:00,602 --> 00:11:01,701
- I think someone pulled me back.
- What?

335
00:11:01,702 --> 00:11:02,801
(Both of them run to the side.)

336
00:11:02,802 --> 00:11:04,202
- What?
- He picked one right away.

337
00:11:06,332 --> 00:11:08,401
(Comic book: Mieum, hieung, chieut)

338
00:11:08,402 --> 00:11:09,942
- Hurry up.
- What is that?

339
00:11:11,272 --> 00:11:13,041
(Television: Tiguet, rieul, bieup, jieut)

340
00:11:13,042 --> 00:11:14,112
Hurry up.

341
00:11:14,412 --> 00:11:15,842
(Aggressive)

342
00:11:16,952 --> 00:11:18,012
What's going on?

343
00:11:18,852 --> 00:11:20,082
Comic book.

344
00:11:20,182 --> 00:11:22,022
- Television.
- Go.

345
00:11:23,822 --> 00:11:24,822
Television...

346
00:11:24,823 --> 00:11:26,223
(DinDin, the 2nd player, sets out.)

347
00:11:26,292 --> 00:11:28,161
(He quickly starts running.)

348
00:11:28,162 --> 00:11:29,191
- I'm next.
- Go.

349
00:11:29,192 --> 00:11:30,561
(Jong Min sets out immediately too.)

350
00:11:30,562 --> 00:11:32,932
Jong Min, get the chair!

351
00:11:33,332 --> 00:11:35,031
Get the chair!

352
00:11:35,032 --> 00:11:36,331
(Joon calls out, "chair.")

353
00:11:36,332 --> 00:11:37,871
(He brings the chair.)

354
00:11:37,872 --> 00:11:39,231
- What's that?
- A chair.

355
00:11:39,232 --> 00:11:40,341
Look.

356
00:11:40,342 --> 00:11:42,222
- I see. They took the card.
- In the middle...

357
00:11:42,972 --> 00:11:45,272
(Team Se Yoon has already gotten the jieut card.)

358
00:11:45,442 --> 00:11:46,482
Joon, come on!

359
00:11:47,042 --> 00:11:48,142
This is driving me crazy.

360
00:11:49,542 --> 00:11:51,022
- They already got it.
- What's that?

361
00:11:51,752 --> 00:11:53,152
- What is it?
- A pencil sharpener.

362
00:11:53,322 --> 00:11:54,722
- DinDin.
- Pencil...

363
00:11:55,222 --> 00:11:56,622
sharper.

364
00:11:57,052 --> 00:11:58,121
Sharper?

365
00:11:58,122 --> 00:11:59,122
- It's a sharpener.
- A sharpener.

366
00:11:59,123 --> 00:12:00,761
- A sharpener.
- It's a sharpener.

367
00:12:00,762 --> 00:12:01,762
What?

368
00:12:01,763 --> 00:12:03,632
- Isn't it a pencil sharper?
- Sharpener.

369
00:12:03,732 --> 00:12:04,762
Really?

370
00:12:05,132 --> 00:12:06,732
Come on. Why isn't it a pencil sharper?

371
00:12:07,832 --> 00:12:08,832
I'm so tired.

372
00:12:08,833 --> 00:12:11,131
(He goes back to school to put the pencil sharpener back.)

373
00:12:11,132 --> 00:12:12,202
Eraser.

374
00:12:13,742 --> 00:12:15,041
Television.

375
00:12:15,042 --> 00:12:16,372
(DinDin picks an eraser.)

376
00:12:16,872 --> 00:12:19,342
("Eraser" and "television" both have jieut.)

377
00:12:20,542 --> 00:12:22,141
(It won't work because of jieut.)

378
00:12:22,142 --> 00:12:24,611
(But he keeps on running hard.)

379
00:12:24,612 --> 00:12:26,152
- There's nothing.
- I'm so tired.

380
00:12:26,282 --> 00:12:27,382
What is it?

381
00:12:27,482 --> 00:12:28,921
Come on! There's jieut in television.

382
00:12:28,922 --> 00:12:31,122
(He realizes his error rather late.)

383
00:12:31,322 --> 00:12:32,522
Eraser.

384
00:12:33,222 --> 00:12:34,362
Comic book.

385
00:12:35,162 --> 00:12:36,221
A microscope.

386
00:12:36,222 --> 00:12:37,961
(This time, he grabs a microscope.)

387
00:12:37,962 --> 00:12:38,991
A comic book.

388
00:12:38,992 --> 00:12:40,762
(A comic book is already been chosen.)

389
00:12:44,102 --> 00:12:45,832
They both have hieung.

390
00:12:46,502 --> 00:12:47,542
Come on.

391
00:12:48,042 --> 00:12:50,212
(How many times will he come back to school?)

392
00:12:51,172 --> 00:12:53,311
(He must've been quite shocked by the pencil sharpener error.)

393
00:12:53,312 --> 00:12:55,212
- They already got the card.
- Oh, right.

394
00:12:55,582 --> 00:12:56,981
Television. A comic book.

395
00:12:56,982 --> 00:12:58,051
- A comic book.
- A phone.

396
00:12:58,052 --> 00:12:59,882
- A phone.
- He said phones counted too

397
00:13:00,222 --> 00:13:01,251
- Phone.
- Phone.

398
00:13:01,252 --> 00:13:02,252
- Go ahead.
- Phone.

399
00:13:02,522 --> 00:13:03,522
- What did you get?
- Phone.

400
00:13:03,523 --> 00:13:04,592
- Phone.
- That's good.

401
00:13:04,792 --> 00:13:06,151
- You went with "phone?"
- Yes, he said I could.

402
00:13:06,152 --> 00:13:07,261
What should we get?

403
00:13:07,262 --> 00:13:09,162
(Only 11 consonant cards remain.)

404
00:13:09,292 --> 00:13:11,461
What else could I bring? There's nothing.

405
00:13:11,462 --> 00:13:14,362
(As he's in a hurry, he can't think of a word.)

406
00:13:15,462 --> 00:13:16,571
(Joon's camera)

407
00:13:16,572 --> 00:13:17,602
Will this work?

408
00:13:18,372 --> 00:13:20,402
(He brings it back just in case.)

409
00:13:21,142 --> 00:13:22,502
- What's that?
- This is...

410
00:13:23,142 --> 00:13:24,441
- This is...
- An oven?

411
00:13:24,442 --> 00:13:26,012
- What is it?
- This is...

412
00:13:26,412 --> 00:13:27,982
a lid!

413
00:13:28,712 --> 00:13:30,282
- A lid?
- A lid!

414
00:13:30,612 --> 00:13:31,681
- A lid.
- No one took the cards.

415
00:13:31,682 --> 00:13:33,822
- There you go. You got it.
- This is great.

416
00:13:34,352 --> 00:13:35,651
Right here. We have another card.

417
00:13:35,652 --> 00:13:36,852
- Right here.
- Give it to me.

418
00:13:37,052 --> 00:13:38,122
- A lid? My gosh.
- A lid.

419
00:13:38,552 --> 00:13:39,591
That's good.

420
00:13:39,592 --> 00:13:41,222
You know what? Look.

421
00:13:41,392 --> 00:13:43,531
- You should go now.
- No, wait.

422
00:13:43,532 --> 00:13:45,892
Leung, nieun, digeut, siot, giyeok, kieuk...

423
00:13:46,392 --> 00:13:47,962
- Okay.
- You can do it.

424
00:13:48,562 --> 00:13:49,801
Leung, nieun, digeut, siot, giyeok, kieuk,

425
00:13:49,802 --> 00:13:51,002
and the double consonants.

426
00:13:51,932 --> 00:13:55,302
(He takes something out from the cassette player.)

427
00:13:55,772 --> 00:13:58,372
(Is that paper?)

428
00:13:58,872 --> 00:14:00,382
- Hey.
- Yes.

429
00:14:00,912 --> 00:14:03,312
- Lyrics.
- Lyrics.

430
00:14:03,912 --> 00:14:05,312
- You guys are good!
- Okay.

431
00:14:05,982 --> 00:14:07,381
- Lyrics.
- Lyrics.

432
00:14:07,382 --> 00:14:08,451
All right.

433
00:14:08,452 --> 00:14:09,921
- The lyrics are written here.
- We need giyeok, nieun, kieuk...

434
00:14:09,922 --> 00:14:11,628
Giyeok, nieun, kieuk, and the double consonants.

435
00:14:11,652 --> 00:14:12,752
- Hey.
- Go.

436
00:14:12,892 --> 00:14:13,961
- Okay. Go!
- Giyeok, nieun, kieuk...

437
00:14:13,962 --> 00:14:15,768
Giyeok, nieun, kieuk, ssangbieup, ssangsiot, and ssangjieut.

438
00:14:15,792 --> 00:14:18,432
(The gap has already doubled.)

439
00:14:18,962 --> 00:14:20,161
What's taking DinDin so long?

440
00:14:20,162 --> 00:14:21,808
- He's bringing it. What is it?
- What is it?

441
00:14:21,832 --> 00:14:22,932
A comic book.

442
00:14:23,602 --> 00:14:24,632
A xylophone.

443
00:14:24,932 --> 00:14:27,241
- We've got nothing.
- No. Rieul is taken.

444
00:14:27,242 --> 00:14:28,541
There's rieul in television.

445
00:14:28,542 --> 00:14:30,471
(He only finds out after coming back.)

446
00:14:30,472 --> 00:14:33,112
Come on. What's wrong with him?

447
00:14:33,782 --> 00:14:34,811
Come on.

448
00:14:34,812 --> 00:14:35,841
(Something's off with DinDin, the smart guy.)

449
00:14:35,842 --> 00:14:37,782
Please!

450
00:14:38,512 --> 00:14:39,682
What is it?

451
00:14:39,922 --> 00:14:41,222
Gold. Nothing there.

452
00:14:41,422 --> 00:14:43,452
Giyeok was taken just now.

453
00:14:44,122 --> 00:14:46,252
It's gone.

454
00:14:47,162 --> 00:14:48,292
What is it?

455
00:14:48,962 --> 00:14:50,192
- What is it?
- What is it?

456
00:14:50,392 --> 00:14:51,432
Chieut is taken.

457
00:14:52,262 --> 00:14:53,532
I can't do it!

458
00:14:55,002 --> 00:14:57,202
- Cell phone. Come on.
- What are you doing?

459
00:14:57,802 --> 00:14:58,802
Hurry up!

460
00:14:58,803 --> 00:14:59,901
(Se Yoon hasn't even played yet.)

461
00:14:59,902 --> 00:15:01,072
What's wrong with him?

462
00:15:01,172 --> 00:15:02,741
I'll give you one more minute.

463
00:15:02,742 --> 00:15:04,542
Wait. We only have the initials from my turn?

464
00:15:06,912 --> 00:15:08,512
Isn't it pencil sharper?

465
00:15:08,782 --> 00:15:10,051
I won't even get to play.

466
00:15:10,052 --> 00:15:11,452
(He's still on pencil sharpeners.)

467
00:15:11,952 --> 00:15:13,521
It's getting tough now.

468
00:15:13,522 --> 00:15:14,751
(Not a lot of cards remain now.)

469
00:15:14,752 --> 00:15:15,852
Gosh, I don't know.

470
00:15:17,692 --> 00:15:20,591
(Leung, nieun, digeut, kieuk, ssangbieup, ssangsiot, ssangjieut)

471
00:15:20,592 --> 00:15:21,622
Ssangbieup.

472
00:15:22,192 --> 00:15:23,291
Your last 30 seconds!

473
00:15:23,292 --> 00:15:26,431
(He grabs an item when there are only 30 seconds left.)

474
00:15:26,432 --> 00:15:27,502
What's that?

475
00:15:28,002 --> 00:15:29,032
What's that?

476
00:15:29,702 --> 00:15:30,802
He's sulking.

477
00:15:31,272 --> 00:15:32,272
- Money.
- He's sulking.

478
00:15:32,273 --> 00:15:34,102
- He's sulking.
- Money.

479
00:15:34,442 --> 00:15:36,171
- No, that's not right.
- He's sulking.

480
00:15:36,172 --> 00:15:37,571
- That's not it.
- No.

481
00:15:37,572 --> 00:15:38,641
- He's sulking hard.
- What are you doing?

482
00:15:38,642 --> 00:15:40,611
- He's sulking.
- That's not the right letter.

483
00:15:40,612 --> 00:15:41,742
There's nothing else.

484
00:15:41,842 --> 00:15:43,182
Digital camera.

485
00:15:43,552 --> 00:15:44,952
- He got them.
- That's good.

486
00:15:45,152 --> 00:15:46,382
Jieut is taken?

487
00:15:46,722 --> 00:15:48,851
- This won't count?
- No.

488
00:15:48,852 --> 00:15:50,621
- It won't count?
- No.

489
00:15:50,622 --> 00:15:52,652
How about, "pretty?"

490
00:15:53,092 --> 00:15:54,191
He's pretty.

491
00:15:54,192 --> 00:15:55,561
(Leung and ssangbieup?)

492
00:15:55,562 --> 00:15:57,462
Beauty is all subjective.

493
00:15:57,732 --> 00:15:58,961
- He was an older brother!
- It's...

494
00:15:58,962 --> 00:16:00,532
- Older brother.
- Older brother.

495
00:16:00,702 --> 00:16:01,831
Older brother.

496
00:16:01,832 --> 00:16:03,232
- Older brother.
- Great.

497
00:16:03,402 --> 00:16:04,402
He was an older brother.

498
00:16:04,403 --> 00:16:05,731
- He is older than me.
- Gosh, you'll allow this?

499
00:16:05,732 --> 00:16:07,642
- That counts.
- He's older than me.

500
00:16:08,042 --> 00:16:09,241
- He was a cool older brother.
- All right.

501
00:16:09,242 --> 00:16:10,672
- Great.
- Great.

502
00:16:11,472 --> 00:16:12,512
That's it.

503
00:16:12,772 --> 00:16:15,041
Let me check if he should be called an older brother.

504
00:16:15,042 --> 00:16:16,642
That's Benjamin Franklin.

505
00:16:16,982 --> 00:16:19,881
I'm going to check if he had a younger sister.

506
00:16:19,882 --> 00:16:21,752
He could be an older brother to someone.

507
00:16:23,592 --> 00:16:25,192
Benjamin Franklin...

508
00:16:25,622 --> 00:16:28,462
was the youngest son in a family of 17 sons.

509
00:16:29,062 --> 00:16:30,631
- But hear me out.
- He was the youngest son.

510
00:16:30,632 --> 00:16:31,831
- So he had no sisters.
- Come on.

511
00:16:31,832 --> 00:16:33,992
- To some, he was an older brother.
- No, I was wrong.

512
00:16:34,062 --> 00:16:35,361
He was the youngest son.

513
00:16:35,362 --> 00:16:36,801
But he had three younger sisters.

